Analysis of Movie Data from IMDB and Box Office Mojo

Tuo Hu

1. Introduction

Each year, the movie industry produces more movies, higher-budget movies, and more genres of media compete for audience attention. Between 2000 and 2010, only 36% of movies had profitable box-office returns. Therefore, missing an opportunity to make a commercia success movie has never been more costly than ever. And every decision the production company make has to takes more than ever into count.


Both imdb.com and tmdb.com are websites that serve as online databases of world film industry. Those websites contain a large amount of public data on films over the past few decades. Especially in the past few years, this kind of rating website has become many audiences’ first choice to examine the quality of movies. In addition to gaining tremendous profit commercially from a commercial success movie, a “great” movie also entertains the audience, and may even improve an individual’s perception.


By examining the historical data from thousands of movies over several decades, we are able to get statistically meaningful results that may help provide recommendations for the industry. As the saying goes, knowledge is power, and data analytics gives us the ability to turn raw data into valuable knowledge. However, is a highly-rated movie necessarily mean to be a commercial success movie? That what we are going to discuss throughout this project.

Obviously, the dataset we got after merging has some redundant columns. The “id” and “imdb_id” columns will not help us analyze any data; therefore, they need to be dropped. Some columns are presented in array forms with raw string datatype, we need to store them in a list using split method.


Considering that we will make a prediction of IMDB ratings, movies with very limited votes are not very reliable, therefore, we drop those movies whose votes are less than 50. The dataset included some movies which are lacking budget or revenue data. When we look into those movies, we found that it was a common case for individual movies who do not have access to release movies in theaters. Since our hypothesis needs to count revenue and budget factors, we decided to drop those movies lacking budget and revenue data and those whose revenue and budget are less than $5000.

def countNumber(column):
    count = dict()
    for row in column:
        for ele in row:
            if ele in count:
                count[ele] += 1
            else:
                count[ele] = 1
    return count
print(df_top_revenue.mean())

def countN(column):
    count = dict()
    for row in column:
        for ele in row:
            if ele in count:
                count[ele] += 1
            else:
                count[ele] = 1
    return count

from scipy import spatial

def angle(movie1, movie2):
    dis_tot = 0
    iterlist = [[movie1.genres_bin, movie2.genres_bin],
                [movie1.director_bin, movie2.director_bin],
                [movie1.cast_bin, movie2.cast_bin]]
    for b1, b2 in iterlist:
        if(1 not in b1) or (1 not in b2):
            dis = 1
        else:
            dis = spatial.distance.cosine(b1, b2)
        dis_tot += dis
    return dis_tot

In [210]:
def predictor(new_movie):
    movie_bin = pd.Series()
    movie_bin['genres_bin'] = binary(genres, new_movie['genres'])
    movie_bin['director_bin'] = binary(directors, new_movie['director'])
    movie_bin['actors_bin'] = binary(actors, new_movie['cast'])

    vote = df3.copy()
    vote['angle'] = [angle(vote.iloc[i], movie_bin) for i in range(len(vote))]
    vote = vote.sort_values('angle')
    vote_avg = np.mean(vote.imdb_rating[0:10])
    return vote_avg
